2. list-style-position ⭐⭐

Controls whether the bullet is inside or outside the content.

Syntax

list-style-position: outside;

or

list-style-position: inside;
Outside (Default)
ul{
    list-style-position: outside;
}

Output

• Apple is very healthy.
  It contains vitamins.

The text starts after the bullet.

Inside
ul{
    list-style-position: inside;
}

Output

• Apple is very healthy.
It contains vitamins.

The bullet becomes part of the text block.

Example
<ul class="inside">
    <li>This is a very long list item to show how inside works.</li>
</ul>
.inside{
    list-style-position: inside;
}
Difference

Outside

• This is a long sentence
  continues here

Inside

• This is a long sentence
continues here
3. list-style-image ⭐⭐

Instead of bullets, you can use an image.

Syntax

list-style-image: url("star.png");

Example

<ul class="fruit">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
    <li>Orange</li>
</ul>
.fruit{
    list-style-image:url("star.png");
}

Output

⭐ Apple
⭐ Mango
⭐ Orange

The image replaces the default bullet.

Note: If the image cannot be loaded, the browser falls back to the list-style-type (or its default).

Shorthand Property

Instead of writing multiple properties separately, you can combine them.

ul{
    list-style: square inside;
}

Equivalent to

ul{
    list-style-type: square;
    list-style-position: inside;
}

You can also use an image:

ul{
    list-style: url("star.png") inside;
}
Complete Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>

.disc{
    list-style-type:disc;
}

.square{
    list-style-type:square;
}

.circle{
    list-style-type:circle;
}

.none{
    list-style-type:none;
}

.inside{
    list-style-type:square;
    list-style-position:inside;
}

.image{
    list-style-image:url("star.png");
}

</style>
</head>

<body>

<h2>Disc</h2>
<ul class="disc">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
</ul>

<h2>Square</h2>
<ul class="square">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
</ul>

<h2>Circle</h2>
<ul class="circle">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
</ul>

<h2>No Bullet</h2>
<ul class="none">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
</ul>

<h2>Inside Position</h2>
<ul class="inside">
    <li>This is a long list item to demonstrate how list-style-position: inside works.</li>
</ul>

</body>
</html>
Interview Questions
1. What is list-style-type?

It changes the appearance of the list marker (bullet or numbering), such as disc, circle, square, decimal, or none.

2. What is list-style-position?

It specifies whether the list marker appears inside or outside the list item's content box.

3. What is list-style-image?

It replaces the default list marker with a custom image.

4. How do you remove bullets from a list?
ul{
    list-style-type: none;
}
5. What is the shorthand for list styles?
list-style: square inside;
Summary
Property	Purpose	Example
list-style-type	Changes bullet/number style	square, circle, decimal, none
list-style-position	Places marker inside or outside	inside, outside
list-style-image	Uses an image as the marker	url("star.png")
list-style	Shorthand for all list properties	list-style: square inside;

These three properties are enough for beginner to intermediate CSS interviews, and list-style-type: none is especially common for creating navigation menus.

my image is large how to make it to set properly

If your image used in list-style-image is too large, CSS does not provide a direct way to resize list-style-image. Here are the best approaches.

Method 1 (Recommended): Use ::before with an Image

Instead of list-style-image, remove the default bullet and insert your own image.

HTML
<ul class="custom-list">
    <li>Apple</li>
    <li>Mango</li>
    <li>Orange</li>
</ul>
CSS
.custom-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding-left: 0;
}

.custom-list li {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

.custom-list li::before {
    content: "";
    background-image: url("star.png");
    background-size: 20px 20px; /* Resize image */
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    display: inline-block;
    margin-right: 10px;
}

Output

⭐ Apple
⭐ Mango
⭐ Orange

Here you can easily change the size:

background-size: 15px 15px;

or

width: 30px;
height: 30px;
Method 2: Resize the Original Image

If you're using:

ul {
    list-style-image: url("star.png");
}

and star.png is 100 × 100 px, it will appear large because browsers use the image at its original size.

Resize the image itself using an image editor (e.g., to 16 × 16 px or 20 × 20 px) before using it.

Why doesn't width and height work?

Many beginners try this:

ul {
    list-style-image: url("star.png");
    width: 20px;   /* ❌ Doesn't resize the bullet */
    height: 20px;  /* ❌ Doesn't resize the bullet */
}

This does not work because list-style-image doesn't support resizing with CSS.

Interview Tip

Question: Can we resize an image used with list-style-image?

Answer: No. CSS doesn't allow resizing list-style-image directly. The preferred approach is to remove the default marker (list-style: none) and use the ::before pseudo-element with background-image or an <img> element, where you can control the size.
